 the increase in tourism to Otavalo, the diaspora of Otavalo merchants and musicians around the world, changing social relations at home, the growth of indigenous political power, and current debates within the Otavalo community over preserving cultural identity in the face of globalization and transnational migration. Refuting the belief that contact with the wider world inevitably destroys indigenous societies, Meisch demonstrates that Otavalos are preserving many features of their culture while adopting and adapting modern technologies and practices they find useful.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aInternational business enterpriseszEcuadorzOtavalo. 0aOtavalo IndiansxEconomic conditions. 0aOtavalo IndiansxIndustries. 0aOtavalo business enterpriseszEcuadorzOtavalo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798519/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK